{
  "answer": "**Chapter 50 of *Diwan-E-Ghalib* is titled \"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai\".**[^1]\n\nIn ghazal poetry, the **matla** (opening couplet) consists of the first two lines (misraʿas), which set the radif (\"bahut hai\") repeated throughout:\n\n> Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai  \n> Yeh ranj ke kam hai mai-e-gulfaam bahut hai[^2]\n\n**English translation:**  \n\"This weak, failed heart's capacity for pain is more than enough;  \nThe grief that rose-red wine is on the wane is more than enough.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 50, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 50, [p-d3a1ee](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/transliteration/#p-d3a1ee) (transliteration; first paragraph spans the matla).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 50, [p-b39b6a](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/#p-b39b6a).",
